<br>
<br>
<br>
When Mia awoke, she found herself on the floor.  She sat up, and hastily whipped the sleep out of her eyes.  As her vision cleared she realized:  this was not her apartment.  This was hell, or as close to it as she had ever seen.  Mia was sitting in a large pool of blood.  As she scanned the room, she saw blood on the furniture, the walls, even the ceiling.  The place reeked of sweat and blood and excrement.  Mia’s heart boomed within her chest as she stood up and followed the path of blood into the bedroom.  The condition of the bedroom was even worse than that of the living room, for in here she found pieces of flesh mixed in with the blood.  Fragments of bone, scraps of hair, and wet pieces of meat covered everything.  Someone had been ripped apart in here.  Literally, ripped apart.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A sharp pain hit Mia’s stomach and she doubled over, vomit cascading out of her mouth and mixing with the filth on the floor.  It was then that she saw it.  The baby crib in the corner.  With horror she forced herself closer to peer inside.  Tears tore through her eyes when she saw the remains of what had once been a young baby girl.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A crashing sound echoed in from the hallway.  Mia frantically scanned the room looking for something, anything;  a way out.  She found a butcherknife sticking out of the wall, pining a bit of flesh to the drywall.  She yanked the blood soaked blade out and held it loosely in front of her, too scared and nervous to be able to defend herself properly.  The door to the bed room burst open and the room filled with men dressed in blue and black, guns pointed straight at her.  “Freeze!”  one screamed, and another: “put down the weapon!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Mia fell to her knees and dropped the knife, which clattered on the floorboards.  Her vision was so obscured by the tears that she couldn’t see anything.  She couldn’t see the men approach her.  She didn’t see anything until she was given a tissue several hours later at the police station . . .<br>
